<h2>New Mexico Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>New Mexico offers a comprehensive array of incentives and rebates that make solar and energy-efficient HVAC investments highly attractive. The foundation of these incentives begins with the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and related expenses, with no cap on the credit amount for residential installations.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available for solar installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit can be carried forward if it exceeds tax liability in the installation year, and applies to battery storage systems when installed with solar.</li>
<li><strong>New Mexico Solar Tax Credit:</strong> The state offers an additional 10% tax credit for solar installations, capped at \$6,000 for residential systems. This credit can be combined with the federal credit for total savings of up to 40% of installation costs.</li>
<li><strong>PNM Solar Programs:</strong> Public Service Company of New Mexico offers net metering at retail rates, allowing customers to receive full credit for excess solar production. PNM also provides interconnection support and streamlined permitting processes for residential solar installations.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Rebates:</strong> Various municipal utilities throughout New Mexico offer additional rebates for solar and energy efficiency improvements. Albuquerque residents may qualify for additional rebates through the city's environmental programs.</li>
<li><strong>PACE Financing:</strong> Property Assessed Clean Energy financing is available in some New Mexico counties, allowing property owners to finance solar and energy efficiency improvements through property tax assessments with terms up to 20 years.</li>
</ul>

<p>To maximize incentives, homeowners should work with certified installers familiar with local requirements and timing considerations. Tax credits must be claimed in the year of installation, and proper documentation including manufacturer certifications and installation receipts are required. Many homeowners can achieve effective system costs of 50-60% of the gross installation price when combining federal, state, and local incentives.</p>

